```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{hyperref}
\usepackage{lipsum}

\title{Screenwriting Framework Documentation}
\author{Beginner's Guide to Scriptwriting}
\date{}

\begin{document}

\maketitle

\section{1.1 Purpose of This Guide}

This guide is designed to help absolute beginners understand the fundamentals of writing a script, taking them through each step in a structured and easy-to-follow way. Writing a script can seem like a daunting task, especially if you're not familiar with the terminology, the process, or the tools that professional writers use. This guide simplifies these concepts and breaks them down into manageable pieces, showing not just \textit{what} you need to do, but \textit{why} it's important to do it.

The goal is to turn your ideas into a well-organized, engaging script, whether it's for a short film, a feature-length movie, or even a TV series. By following this guide, you will understand how to develop:
\begin{itemize}
  \item A clear \textbf{plot} with a strong structure.
  \item Deep and believable \textbf{characters} that grow throughout the story.
  \item A cohesive \textbf{theme} that ties your story together.
  \item An understanding of the \textbf{tone} and \textbf{genre} that best fit your story.
\end{itemize}

We will explore key elements of screenwriting such as:
\begin{itemize}
  \item The importance of a \textbf{logline}, a concise summary of your story.
  \item How to structure your story using the \textbf{three-act structure}, which is a proven method for pacing and building tension.
  \item How to develop \textbf{character arcs} that show growth or transformation, making your characters feel real and relatable.
\end{itemize}

Throughout this guide, we’ll provide examples of both \textbf{good} and \textbf{bad} practices, so you can see common pitfalls and how to avoid them. The aim is not only to help you write a script but to help you write a \textit{good} script—one that captures the audience’s attention, maintains their interest, and leaves them thinking about your story long after it ends.

\subsection{Why Structure is Important}

A well-structured script is easier to write and far more engaging to watch. Think of a script like building a house: without a solid foundation, the whole thing will fall apart. This guide teaches you how to build that foundation and then add the walls, roof, and final touches in a way that creates a strong and compelling final product. Without structure, even the best ideas can feel scattered, confusing, or unsatisfying to an audience. 

For instance:
\begin{itemize}
  \item \textbf{Good Practice Example}: A script that follows a clear \textbf{three-act structure} (beginning, middle, and end) allows the audience to follow the story easily. A hero is introduced with a problem in Act 1, faces challenges and grows in Act 2, and finally overcomes (or fails) in Act 3. This format is used in most successful films for a reason.
  \item \textbf{Bad Practice Example}: A script with no clear structure can leave the audience confused. Imagine watching a movie where new characters keep popping up without reason, or the story jumps around without explaining why things happen. This is often the result of poor planning and lack of structure.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Who This Guide Is For}

This guide is tailored for:
\begin{enumerate}
  \item \textbf{First-time writers}: If you've never written a script before, this guide will explain the process in a simple, step-by-step manner, removing the mystery of storytelling.
  \item \textbf{Writers looking to improve}: If you’ve tried to write scripts but struggled with getting them finished or making them compelling, this guide will help you refine your process and produce a stronger, more coherent story.
  \item \textbf{Non-writers (e.g., directors or producers)}: If you're a filmmaker, director, or producer looking to understand how to build a better story or how scripts are constructed, this guide will give you the tools to understand the essentials of screenwriting.
\end{enumerate}

\subsection{What This Guide Will Cover}

Here’s a brief overview of what you’ll learn in this guide:
\begin{itemize}
  \item \textbf{Creating a Logline}: A one or two-sentence summary of your story that captures the essence of your plot and characters. This keeps your story focused and clear from the start.
  \item \textbf{Understanding Genre and Tone}: We will help you choose the right genre and tone for your story, ensuring that your script meets audience expectations and creates the desired emotional impact.
  \item \textbf{Building Characters with Depth}: Instead of flat, one-dimensional characters, you'll learn how to create characters with internal conflicts, desires, and motivations. Understanding the difference between what a character \textbf{wants} (their external goal) and what they \textbf{need} (their internal journey) is key to building an engaging character arc.
  \item \textbf{The Three-Act Structure}: The backbone of your story. Act 1 introduces the characters and world, Act 2 complicates their journey, and Act 3 brings everything to a satisfying conclusion. We'll break down how to pace your story so that it flows smoothly from start to finish.
  \item \textbf{Thematic Consistency}: How to ensure your theme (the deeper message or meaning of your story) resonates throughout the script, reinforcing the plot and character actions.
  \item \textbf{Creating Dynamic Scenes}: Every scene should serve a purpose—either advancing the plot or revealing something about the characters. We’ll show you how to ensure that each scene has tension, stakes, and a clear goal.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Examples to Illustrate Each Step}

For each step, this guide will use \textbf{examples} to illustrate good practices and common mistakes. These examples will help clarify how to apply the concepts you’re learning:
\begin{itemize}
  \item \textbf{Good Practice Example}: "In \textit{The Lion King}, Simba’s journey is clear. His external goal is to reclaim his throne, but his internal need is to overcome his guilt and accept his place in the circle of life. These two threads drive the entire narrative, creating a cohesive and emotional story."
  \item \textbf{Bad Practice Example}: "In an unfocused script, a character might have no clear motivation or arc, leading to disjointed scenes that don’t add up. For example, if a character starts a story wanting to save the world but halfway through switches to a different, unrelated goal (with no explanation), the audience will feel lost and disconnected."
\end{itemize}

\subsection{The End Goal}

By the end of this guide, you should feel confident in your ability to:
\begin{itemize}
  \item Plan and structure your script with a clear beginning, middle, and end.
  \item Develop complex, multi-layered characters that audiences will care about.
  \item Write dynamic scenes that advance the plot and reveal character.
  \item Refine your script through revision, ensuring that it’s polished and coherent.
\end{itemize}

Screenwriting is both an art and a craft. While creativity plays a big role, understanding the underlying structure and techniques used by successful writers can make the process smoother and help you avoid common mistakes. With the tools provided in this guide, you’ll be equipped to bring your story to life on the page in a professional and compelling way.

In the following sections, we will dive into the key elements of writing a script, starting with understanding how to develop your story overview, character creation, and plot structure.

\end{document}
```

