```latex
\section{2. Story Overview}

The story overview is the foundation of your script. It includes elements that define the core of your story, such as the title, logline, themes, and genre. Each of these elements will help you shape the direction of your script and maintain a clear focus throughout the writing process. In this section, we will start by discussing the importance of choosing the right title for your story.

\subsection{2.1 Title Creation}

The title is often the first impression your story makes on the audience. A good title not only grabs attention but also gives a sense of the tone, theme, or subject matter of the script. While coming up with the perfect title can be challenging, it's essential for establishing the mood and expectations before the audience even starts reading or watching.

\subsubsection{What Makes a Good Title?}

A good title should be:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Relevant to the Story:} The title should reflect the core idea, theme, or key element of the story. It could hint at the setting, the protagonist, or the central conflict.
    \item \textbf{Memorable:} A title should be easy to remember and distinct, making it stand out among other scripts or movies.
    \item \textbf{Evocative:} It should evoke curiosity or emotion. Whether it's a sense of mystery, excitement, or drama, the title should compel the audience to want to know more.
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Good Practice Example}: 
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textit{Jurassic Park} — Immediately gives the audience a sense of the setting (a park) and suggests the key element (dinosaurs) of the story. It’s both specific and intriguing.
    \item \textit{The Dark Knight} — Refers to the protagonist, Batman, and sets a dark, serious tone for the movie. It reflects both the character and the theme of the film.
    \item \textit{Inception} — The title is abstract and intriguing, suggesting deep, complex ideas. It fits well with the film’s exploration of dreams and reality.
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Bad Practice Example}: 
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textit{The Guy Who Fights} — This title is too vague and generic. It doesn't provide any insight into the unique aspects of the story, making it forgettable.
    \item \textit{Love in the Time of Dragons and Battles} — Overly complicated titles can be difficult to remember or understand, and they might confuse the audience about the genre or tone of the story.
    \item \textit{Mystery of 1234} — While it implies mystery, the title is too cryptic and lacks connection to any identifiable theme or character, making it unappealing.
\end{itemize}

\subsubsection{How Titles Set the Tone for the Story}

The title can give the audience an idea of the mood and style of your script. Whether your story is a light-hearted comedy, an intense thriller, or an epic adventure, the title should give a clue about the tone.

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Serious Tone:} Titles like \textit{The Godfather} or \textit{Schindler's List} immediately suggest a serious, dramatic story.
    \item \textbf{Humorous Tone:} Titles like \textit{Dumb and Dumber} or \textit{The 40-Year-Old Virgin} indicate that the story will have a comedic, light-hearted tone.
    \item \textbf{Mysterious/Thriller Tone:} Titles like \textit{Gone Girl} or \textit{Shutter Island} suggest a suspenseful, mysterious atmosphere, making the audience expect twists and tension.
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Good Practice Example}: 
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textit{Get Out} — This title sets an immediate tone of urgency and fear, which matches the tense, horror-thriller nature of the movie.
    \item \textit{La La Land} — The title reflects the whimsical, dreamlike quality of the film, which suits its blend of romance and musical fantasy.
    \item \textit{No Country for Old Men} — The title gives a sense of foreboding and existential struggle, setting the tone for a grim, dramatic film.
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Bad Practice Example}: 
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textit{Fun Time Adventures} — If this title were attached to a thriller or horror script, it would set the wrong expectations for the audience, who might anticipate a children’s adventure movie instead.
    \item \textit{The Best Friend Ever} — This title sounds too light for a serious drama about betrayal or deep emotional conflict, causing a mismatch between title and tone.
\end{itemize}

The title plays a crucial role in how your story is perceived from the very beginning. By ensuring it is relevant, memorable, and evocative, you set the right expectations for your audience, giving them a glimpse of the world they’re about to enter.

```

