\subsection{4.3 Act 1 - The Setup}

\textbf{Act 1}, also known as the setup, serves as the foundation for the entire story. In this act, the characters, setting, and conflict are introduced, and the audience is given a clear sense of the protagonist’s world before the main plot kicks into motion. The setup is critical for establishing the stakes and for creating an emotional connection between the audience and the characters.

\subsubsection{The Role of Act 1 in Establishing Characters, Setting, and Conflict}

Act 1 introduces the main characters and provides context for their world, goals, and relationships. It also establishes the primary conflict that will drive the story forward. By the end of Act 1, the audience should have a clear understanding of:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{The Protagonist:} Who the main character is, their personality, goals, and what they stand to lose or gain.
    \item \textbf{The Setting:} The world in which the story takes place. This includes not only the physical location but also the time period, social structure, and rules of the world (especially in sci-fi or fantasy genres).
    \item \textbf{The Central Conflict:} The challenge or problem that the protagonist must face. This conflict is often introduced early but doesn’t fully develop until after the inciting incident.
\end{itemize}

The first act should establish a sense of normalcy for the protagonist’s life, which will later be disrupted by the central conflict. It’s important to build enough context and depth around the characters and their world so that when the plot accelerates, the audience is invested in the outcome.

\textbf{Good Practice Example:} 
\begin{itemize}
    \item In \textit{Spider-Man: Homecoming}, Act 1 introduces Peter Parker’s life as a high school student, his relationships with Aunt May and his friends, and his double life as Spider-Man. The setting of New York City is established, and the audience is introduced to the world Peter is trying to navigate—balancing school, friendships, and his desire to prove himself as a superhero.
    \item In \textit{The Hunger Games}, Act 1 sets up the dystopian world of Panem, the strict divisions between the districts, and the oppressive government led by President Snow. The central conflict—the upcoming Hunger Games—is introduced, along with Katniss’s motivation to protect her sister.
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Bad Practice Example:} 
\begin{itemize}
    \item If Act 1 fails to clearly establish the protagonist’s goals or the stakes of the story, the audience may feel disconnected or confused when the main conflict begins. For example, a film that spends too much time on irrelevant details without focusing on the protagonist’s motivations may lose the audience’s interest before the plot kicks in.
    \item A setup that introduces too many characters or subplots without focusing on the central narrative can overwhelm the audience, making it difficult to understand who the protagonist is and what their journey will entail.
\end{itemize}

\subsubsection{The Importance of the Inciting Incident}

The \textbf{inciting incident} is the event that disrupts the protagonist’s normal world and sets the plot into motion. This moment is crucial because it pushes the protagonist out of their comfort zone and presents them with a challenge or opportunity they cannot ignore. The inciting incident should occur early in Act 1 (typically within the first 10-15 minutes of a film) to maintain momentum and engage the audience.

\textbf{What Makes a Strong Inciting Incident:}
\begin{itemize}
    \item It should force the protagonist to take action or make a significant decision.
    \item It should introduce or escalate the central conflict of the story.
    \item It should create a clear shift from the protagonist’s ordinary world to the main narrative.
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Good Practice Example:} 
\begin{itemize}
    \item In \textit{The Matrix}, the inciting incident occurs when Neo is contacted by Morpheus and given the choice between the red pill and the blue pill. By choosing the red pill, Neo is pulled into the world of the Matrix, which completely disrupts his normal life and sets the main plot into motion.
    \item In \textit{Finding Nemo}, the inciting incident happens when Nemo is captured by a scuba diver. This event forces Marlin, Nemo’s father, to leave the safety of his home and embark on a journey across the ocean to rescue his son.
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Bad Practice Example:} 
\begin{itemize}
    \item A weak inciting incident might fail to have a significant impact on the protagonist’s life or might feel disconnected from the main conflict. For example, if an inciting incident occurs but the protagonist takes no action or is unaffected by it, the audience may lose interest in the unfolding plot.
\end{itemize}

\subsubsection{Examples of How Act 1 Introduces the Protagonist’s World}

Act 1 is responsible for giving the audience enough context about the protagonist’s world to understand what is at stake when the conflict begins. This includes not only the physical setting but also the relationships, internal struggles, and the social or political dynamics that define the protagonist’s life.

\textbf{Examples:}
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Inception:} Act 1 introduces Dom Cobb’s world of corporate espionage using dream-sharing technology. The audience learns about Cobb’s skills, his personal loss (the death of his wife), and his goal of reuniting with his children. The setup also introduces the concept of inception, which will drive the plot forward.

    \item \textbf{Star Wars: A New Hope:} Act 1 introduces Luke Skywalker’s ordinary life on Tatooine, where he is a farm boy dreaming of adventure. The setting of a galaxy under the control of the Empire is established, as well as Luke’s relationships with his aunt and uncle. The inciting incident occurs when Luke discovers the message from Princess Leia, which pulls him into the Rebel cause.

    \item \textbf{The Devil Wears Prada:} Act 1 introduces Andrea (Andy) Sachs, a recent college graduate looking for a career in journalism. The world of high fashion is introduced when she lands a job at a prestigious fashion magazine under the demanding editor-in-chief, Miranda Priestly. The inciting incident occurs when Andy is hired, which sets the stage for the main conflict between Andy’s values and the fashion industry.
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Bad Practice Example:} 
\begin{itemize}
    \item A setup that fails to introduce the protagonist’s world clearly can leave the audience confused or unengaged. For example, if the setting or the protagonist’s relationships are not clearly defined in Act 1, the audience may struggle to understand the stakes or why the protagonist’s journey matters.
\end{itemize}

Act 1 lays the groundwork for everything that follows in the script. By introducing the protagonist’s world, establishing key relationships, and presenting the central conflict through a strong inciting incident, the setup ensures that the audience is emotionally invested in the story and eager to follow the protagonist on their journey.

```

